annotations:
What could you say
 To a man with a gun?
 Could you say that I’m on my way home
 And I’m already late?

This could be referring to the number of school shootings and gun violence that occurs in the United States every year. Hana Vu is singing about how words are crucial but difficult to say what you mean, especially when your life is on the line.

annotations: Take the Red Line into downtown

This line could be referencing the New York City subway system, also known as the MTA, where the “red line” consists of train 1, 2, and 3. This line runs north to south or “Uptown” to “Downtown”, and it is literally represented by a red line on the subway map.

If I could ever change things
 If I could ever forget
 I would be no longer living
If Hana could ever go back in time and change things, she would not be the matured person she is right now

description.plain:
In an interview with NME before the song’s release, Vu said about the song : https://www.nme.com/blogs/nme-radar/hana-vu-public-storage-interview-3064968

“I was thinking that New Years Eve is kind of everybody’s birthday; you’re reflecting on your life and you have hopes for the future, but you’re ultimately sad every time the year passes and you aren’t who you wanted to be. That was sort of the ethos for that song.”

description.plain: The bittersweet “Mr Lonely” unravels gently across strums and strings. Calling it a response of sorts to Bobby Vinton’s 1962 ballad of a homesick soldier, Vu explains, “I thought that the sentiments of the original song were almost pathetic when put into today’s context.” While this correspondence back to Mr. Lonely delivers a real-talk refute of his starry-eyed love, Vu’s character serves it with compassion. “Quit your longing / it’s alright,” she sings, ultimately suggesting that “it’s better to be alone.”

description.plain: “Parking Lot” chugs at full speed; motorik bass and drum patterns collide with buzzing guitar and urgent lines of introspection. She pins the rugged indie rock sound to her teenage years, playing parking lot and backyard shows. “I was just reflecting on how my perspective on music, performance, existence has changed since then and how differently I go about those things now,” says Vu.
